  "dateModified": "2026-04-02",
  "datePublished": "2026-04-02",
  "description": "Perennial herb from Asteraceae, native to Central Asia (Caucasus, western Asia). Hardy zones 3-9. Herbaceous perennial 0.8-1.5 m tall with finely pinnately-divided feathery foliage (hence \"filipendulina\" = threadlike leaves). Produces dense, flat-topped inflorescences (corymbs) of golden-yellow tiny disk florets. Named for Achilles—historically used as wound treatment for millennia (Trojan War mythology). Dye plant: quercetin and luteolin produce yellow-gold color. Flat-topped flower clusters function as landing pads for beneficial insects (parasitoid wasps, tachinid flies). Drought-tolerant, long-lived, cut-flower cultivar.",
